t, or I could update elasticsearch.yml with the client settings—but that would require a restart. Since the task asks to avoid restarting if possible, I should prioritize using the reload_secure_settings mechanism for credentials and see if I can handle the endpoint configuration through the repository settings alone. I could set `path_style_access` in elasticsearch.yml as a static setting, though that would require a restart. The real question is whether MinIO even needs it—modern versions support both access styles, but virtual-hosted style might fail with DNS resolution since there's no wildcard for the bucket subdomain. Path-style access would be the safer bet to avoid those DNS issues. deprecated or handled differently in 8.x. Let me check the actual Elasticsearch 8.11.1 documentation for the repository-s3 settings to see what options are available at the repository level versus the client level.\n\nLooking at the repository settings, I can see that `endpoint`, `protocol`, and `path_style_access` can all be configured directly in the `PUT /_snapshot` request body under settings, which means I don't need to modify elasticsearch.yml at all. So my approach will be to create the secure settings secret with the MinIO credentials, update the keystore on each pod using the exec command, and then reload the secure settings via the API.\n\nI should also verify whether `path_style_access` is actually a per-repository setting or just a client-level option—if it turns out to be client-only, I'll need to update elasticsearch.yml and restart. But I'll try the no-restart approach first since the task description suggests the credentials in the secret just need to be configured properly, and if path-style access becomes an issue, I can adjust from there. I can't actually read the keystore values since they're encrypted, but given that the task explicitly asks me to configure secure settings and the `es-secure-settings` secret doesn't exist yet, the current credentials are likely incorrect or missing. I should set them to the MinIO root credentials (`minioadmin`/`minioadmin`). I also notice there are no S3 endpoint settings in the elasticsearch.yml file, so I'll need to configure those as well when registering the repository.\n\nLooking at the pod timestamps, the ES cluster was restarted 16-19 minutes ago while MinIO just came up 3 minutes ago, which suggests the keystore values were set from an earlier attempt and probably don't match the current MinIO instance. My approach should be to create the `es-secure-settings` secret with the correct MinIO credentials, update the keystore, and then set up the repository with the proper endpoint configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3044,"cache_read_input_tokens":43740,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3044},"output_tokens":41,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"005bc948-7599-4a23-a366-be6cfbf4dfac","uuid":"381298ba-3d17-4936-a02f-54c2ff74f47f","request_id":"req_011CcQhHtu4nWn1GXEeHsjJa"}
